{"attack":true,"case":"The target violates std-crit-design clause (1): the 'mechanism' must name the specific regime condition in measurable quantities (candidate base error rate, critic precision and recall, ensemble size k), not an aspiration or a non-executable curve. The target explicitly disclaims a point in (base error, precision, recall, k) space, substituting a stochastic-dominance existential ('there exists a threshold tau ... if and only if the critic's score distribution for wrong-majority sets stochastically dominates its score distribution for right-majority sets'). That is a distributional property, not a pre-registrable operating point with numeric precision/recall and k. Worse, the claim asserts the harness strictly beats self-consistency only when effective per-question FPR is near zero while maintaining nonzero recall on wrong sets, yet the proposal's own prose_notes set the concrete targets as FPR < 0.1 and recall > 0.3 — values for which 'near zero' and 'nonzero' are unbounded and do not pin a falsifiable regime. The mechanism is therefore not stated in the required measurable quantities. The target also skirts the FORBIDDEN CASE UNDER TRIAL by listing it under scope.excludes, but excluding the very refutation condition does not make the proposal's forbidden cases measurable by the repository harness: the stated forbidden cases require a KS test and a threshold sweep over a confidence score that the existing validation harness does not produce, and the proposed 60 new questions are outside this repository's candidate pool, violating the shared-pool and rerun-harness honesty requirement of std-crit-design clause (3). Because the forbidden cases depend on a new prompt format and new questions, they cannot be measured by rerunning this repository's validation harness.","counterexample":null}